), consistently placing P. c. relictus from Peleng close to P. c. stentor from Sulawesi, although the concatenated tree built from genome-wide loci was in conflict, placing P. c. relictus closer to P. c. sulanus . Coincidentally, the majority tree with a basal placement of sulanus (topology 1 in
) is also the arrangement that would be supported by the extraordinarily divergent plumage of sulanus , making it unique among all leaftoiler subspecies.

Pairwise divergences between the subspecies (as determined by ND2 distances) were relatively low (0.3-1.7%; 

), at levels generally accepted to be below the species threshold for birds [(~2-3%; (
100, 10 1
)], consistent with the current proposed subspecies status. These ND2 divergences further supported the majority tree (topology 1 in 

) by consistently rendering 
P. c. sulanus
as the most deeply diverged subspecies (up to ~1.7%), whereas 
P. c. relictus
and 
P. c. stentor
emerged as only 0.3% diverged.

(
Togian Jungle-Flycatcher
;

